\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The Great Solgi Erg is a sea of sand that scours the eastern rib of the Jandrian continent, and Mandrameen grew up within sight of it, so he grew up with the story of how those dunes came to be. Every time the story was told some details were added, some forgotten, and sometimes even the soul of it changed completely, but the story always started the same: Solraheen made those mountains of sand a long time ago, back when he walked the earth alone. Solitants quip that that is why it is called the Great Solgi Erg, as gi means gift in Old Jandri.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The stage is then set - primordial earth. A blank, flat canvas for His creation. Next comes the inciting event - Solraheen plants a stick in the ground to mark one of His garden\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s six corners, and then he left to who-knows-where to measure out the rest of it. His passing along the surface of the earth kicked up the first wind, the Shulsai, and this breeze circled the earth and came back around to puff upon the planted stick. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 After an hour, a little embryo of a sand dune built up in the stick\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s lee. Another hour more, and the dune swallowed up the stick, for sand attracts sand attracts sand, and soon the Primal Erg was belly-full and rolling across the surface of the world, leaving littler ergs in its wake.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 This is where the stories begin to diverge, because people disagree about whether or not all of this was intentional. Those who believe it wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t were heretics, and had to tell story in hushed tones and only to discerning company. And they don\u8217\'92t call it the Soldgi Erg. They call it the Soltima Erg - tima akin to shame.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 They claimed that if Solraheen had intended for the dunes to form, he would have built them with his own hands, as he did with everything else in his many other gardens. Why should he want to turn good black earth into a mountain of sand? Why should he wander off into the middle of the world and shape rivers with an eye for beauty, and creatures with an eye for complexity, while he left a Erg to struggle up on it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s own, a basic sameness of stuff with no redeeming qualities in the design?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The answer was clear; it had no redeeming qualities because it was not designed at all. All it did was procreate and ripple the wind. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The heretics would go on to say that when Solraheen made it back around the eastern rib of the Jandrian continent and saw what he had accidentally wrought, he panicked and tried to undo it, as evidenced }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He just up and left. Decided not to do it. He gave up.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 That\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s not what happened.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Were they there to see it?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 No. But they have the proof they need. Go out into the Sand and see the rolling dun for yourself and despair.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The Solitants, of course, have a different story. They claim that Solraheen knew the winds, he knew the appetite of the sand, for He made them. It is important to remember that every work of art is defined by its process of creation, and Solraheen, in his infinite wisdom, knew that his hands could only make certain kinds of things; the birds of the air, the fish of the sea, human beings, but this was not enough to satisfy his creativity. He is the ultimate draughtsman, capable of works in different styles, and so he set the forces of the wind and sand into action with, and from this come the dunes. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 See how Solraheen\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s golden light shimmers across Sand? A sweet smelling rose or a pink-petaled poppy would only blemish such beauty, for the dunes themselves are flowers and come in as many varieties.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 There are tidal dunes in the lee of hills, echo dunes on the windward side. Crescent dunes, snake dunes, crater dunes rimmed with grass. Go to the and marvel at the array of parabolic arcs spanning , or the parallel ridges of Seedra, drifting across the desert with mathematical elegance. There are stripes, domes, duckfeet, hairpins, scallops, stars, all varying in size in temperament to rival the any family.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The dunes are pigment, the wind is the brush, and if one could see the from, a}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 And dunes are sound sculptures. They hiss and moan as they move. In a high wind, the dunes smoke and the air is filled with a booming bellow.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The drumming is the avalanching of billions of tiny grains slowing as they reache the bottom of the slip face.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Dunes are creators, too. As they drift across the plain their sand shapes rocks, they grind away at the rough edges and leave behind lumps, almost like fecal matter, but some of these rocks are perfectly globular things. These rocks are a metaphor, the Solitants say, for the true purpose of the Sand; it is not there to , but it has purifying heart. It teaches us lessons if we\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92re willing to listen, it will grind off our rough outer edges.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Plant a leg in the sand, as Solraheen planted his stick, and the wave you create will become a mountain, it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s passing will resound throughout eternity. That\u8217\'92s the first lesson. Mere existence is enough to change the world.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It was a nice thought, but Mandri would always wonder, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Change the world, sure, but change it for the better?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 This thought possessed as he walked with the Ayramun. The sand crunched underfoot, and his footprints little humps in the flat faces, and he wondered if these were enough to build dunes themselves.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri had died disbelieving the Solitants, but now he wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t sure. That sandstorm was the most incredible thing he\u8217\'92d ever seen in his life while sober. And the colors were special, too. Colors in themselves aren\u8217\'92t that interesting, they\u8217\'92re beautiful for a passing moment before the mind turns to , but he was coming around to thinking that what the Solitants said about the desert\u8217\'92s beauty was fundamentally true. At certain times of day the Sand had stark qualities all it\u8217\'92s own.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It just wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t beautiful when the sun directly above.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Or when the wind was blowing too fiercely. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 When the sun was up, the only thing to see was the sad shadow of the ground. And when the wind blows, the sand accumulates. Sand attracts sand attracts sand. It gets into the , under the nails. It choked and stifled, narrowed the world. And this was a real bummer because when the weather was fine, there were things in it to see.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 A half-buried carven monkey from some ancient age. Chilling in the.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 A half-buried corpse of a lizard.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \line \tab A half-buried living lizard. Moteah said it was called a , and she said the creature could live unmoving under the sand for years and years until a rain came, and it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d wake up, mate, lay eggs, and the return to it\u8217\'92s somnolence.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Purl said there were creatures in the sand that, if you can believe it, didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t need to drink water. They could drink water, they knew how to find it, but if and all the roots dried out and all the rivers into cake, then they could feast on these little nuts called, and that alone would keep them alive. ANd it\u8217\'92s only a certain kind of nut. There\u8217\'92s other nuts, but only that one.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri asked if the nut had water in it, and Moteah said no.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 There were things called weeping dunes, large weeping dunes from which water seeps to the surface. Mandri doubted the story. He walked across them and never saw any water. The ground under his feet was dry as far as his toe could dig.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Moto said that men died crawling around weeping dunes, trying to sop their dried tongues on the damp sand. He said it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s not a source of water that\u8217\'92s easy to access.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri told Purl about Gil.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The first night, Ayram said he had to sleep up off the ground. Mandri asked why and Ayram said that he was better off not knowing. Everyone agreed that it was best he didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t know. They made him sleep atop a . Little saucers that they filled wtih water. Little lizards would come in sip, and when Mandri pointed out that they were sipping, Moteah said to shoo the lizards away and keep filling the saucers with water. Mandri thought it was all a prank until he saw a glistening.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram told Seb to not venture so far ahead. He said that from now on we need to stick together. Seb became prickly after that. Would only respond to his name with a despondent sneer.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Here\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s a lucky stone. A hollow tube of rock scrubbed smooth by sand. When Moteah poured water onto it, it\u8217\'92s ruddy surface took on the sheen of glass. Obo said it was a petrified reed.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 There was a deep well, quarried, with stairs zig-zagging down the to the bottom at 200 feet. The wat brackish water and pulling out fish, blind fish with pulpy membranes were there should have been eyes. That night they cooked the fish on a }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 There arose a learned argument between Seb and him own damn self. The premise: If you put a live fish in a barrel filled to the brim with water, the water does not overflow, but if you put in a dead fish, the water does overflow - this argument went on for a long time until Obo asked if Seb had ever tried do it for himself. Seb hadn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t, so he filled a bowl with water, and found that in either case, the bowl overflowed. He did not know what to make of this.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 On the fourth day they crossed a natron flat two miles long and as many wide. It was dry . Seb broke off small chunks of the white stuff and rubbed it on his few remaining teeth. Mandri knew it as a material used in variety of pigments, though he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d never seen a lake of it. A tiny amount mixed in with quartz sand and copper ore made a blue called Campor Blue, called as such because the most vibrant blues came from Campor, where more than an hundred slaves spent their days sorting the quartz sand for impurities grain by grain with tweezers. Only the cleanest, purest grains of crystal were worthy.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Purl found this fact distasteful. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 At night, body still, he could hear Purl breathing and his libido in his ears. He realized why Solitant nibs spewed so much ink to cover the subject of lust.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Dunes drift across the desert but that\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s not an apt description of how they move. The masses themselves drift, but the actual pieces of sand of which they are composed to not drift, or slide such distances. Instead, the strong winds whips the grains of sand into ballistic arcs to barrage whatever lies downwind. The accumulation and so the greater mass seems to but while the waves move, the ocean itself does not.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The wind is allways blowing west, leaving Mandri to wonder how the dunes replenish themselves if they\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92ve been pouring westward into the sea for a millenia.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He asked Obo this, and Obo said that if it were left alone, it Sand would indeed blow itself into the sea. Mandri asked how long it would be until the desert was completely gone, and Obo said it depends.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 On What?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 On whether or not the herds of Jeket and other Hrkan cities could be made sustainable. On whether or not the axes stop coming for the trees. Bare ground gets trampled and this compacts the soil, dries it out, reflects the sun\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s heat, burns the air, sears the air from rain, and then the wind picks up sand and adds it to the Ergs.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 If all the people and all the herds suddenly died?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It would take ten million years for the desert to disappear.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri was relieved to hear such a large number, even if Obo had pulled it out of his ass. It meant that there wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t much of a difference between a world with people in it and a world without them. Either way the desert would be there, a little bigger or a little smaller, it didn\u8217\'92t matter. The world would end long before ten million years had come.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The common thread of Obo\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s ramblings was that he didn\u8217\'92t think highly of human beings. Most of it made sense to Mandri, every mind capable of reason is preoccupied with justifying its own existence.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mzydobo liked to point to the kind of societies that humans made if left without a Mazyd keeper.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 In the age of city temples, there was an Old Jandri custom that forbade anyone from selling land. The purpose was good-natured, as the wise sages of that age had enough history to diagnose the terminal disease of every city - the diastolic concentration of wealth, precipitating bloody revolution. The idea was that in preventing the sale of land, a family could persist for generations regardless of what wolves were up to. Land changed hands only through inheritance. If an old, childless couple found their work too heavy, they could adopt a few straight-backed persons to till their fields and reap the harvests, and the children could keep it on the condition that they provided grain, oil, and clothes to their parents for as long as the old folks lived.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 And what happened to a system of laws so sensibly conceived? Rich landlords seized upon it, bribing judges, capturing councils, and by hook or by crook they forced the poor peasants adopt them as sons, and thus they devoured all arable land by due process of the law.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 This practice of consolidation carried on for more than one hundred years. What began as a few rich, wicked schemers evolved into wicked consortiums of \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93sons\u8221\'94 - shared pools of silver and gold from which the poor were forced to drink in times of drought. Such was the upward flow of land, that a single man was once the adopted child of five-hundred and fifty-two different sets of parents. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 This was the birth of the Old Jandri banking system, and it set the stage for the demise of all of Old Jandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s tribes, for what it spawned could have been predicted by Jandri\u8217\'92s sages: poor unruly masses, open rebellion, civil war, all expertly exploited by the Hrks.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 How do archaeologists find the ancient city? Every mound of dirt is a city. I have yet to find a place in the land of iraq, except in the newly formed delta, on which one can stand and not see two or three cities clearly outlined on the horizon. The worry is not how to find one, but which to choose.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 build a little mound of clay that would raise the foundations of the houses a trifle above the level of the ground. We thus have beginning of the mound. The houses were built with walls of unbaked bricks and plastered with clay. The roofs of the private dwellings were generally thatched and covered with a thick layer of clay that prevented the rain from filtering through. Each year, the plaster on the outside walls had to be renewed. The roofs also got a fresh coating of clay. All the clay that had been washed down from walls and roof was depositedi nthestreet, so the street level gradually increased in height. Also, no provision for the disposal of refuse, if one ate shellfish, the shells were thrown into the street to remain there. If a change was made in the plan of a house, all the bricks would go into the street.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Stillness - but the desert is not still. As a shaping force, the wind has a quality that water lacks: the ability to flow uphill. From the pinnacle of a dune a skein of spindrift is spun into the sky; along a dune-brink, a hundred tiny cyclones shimmy in line; a sheet of sand scuds over a ridge like a spool of paper rushing through a press. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Pushing back against Obo\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s misanthropy was a difficult thing to do with the Mazyd strapped to his back. Mandri well tell Obo that Mazyd\u8217\'92s weren\u8217\'92t doing such a splendid job. }
\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Paintings on rocks of bestiality.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Moteah said the Jeketian fathers suffered from Acedia - the state of not caring or not being concerned with one's position or condition in the world. Mandri couldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t believe there was a word for it. Who feels like that and thinks to make a word for it? Just fucking die and let everyone else go on being human.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Sand is cool beneath the surface.}
\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \fi360\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Obo said that the sand is quartz; anything softer would be ground to dust within a decade. Mandri said the case, then what are the blue maker\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s slaves doing in Compor. Obo said that was just a marketing gimmick. Mandri said it wasn\u8217\'92t, that he knew vibrant blues, and Obo  Each surface grain accumulates a rind of ferric oxide, and it is this that accounts for the arabian dune\u8217\'92s characterisitic redness. }
\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The strangest thing was a butterfly, of a kind he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d never seen.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 You are the poorest person I know. You suffer from a poverty of thought.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Big section where Mazydobo explains to Purl.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Fucking asshole.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 No, it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s a good thing.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The reason you cannot control me is because you are too kind. You don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 really}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  want to kill people.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 I\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92ve killed people.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Yes, but you didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t want to do it. You understand? You have a soft character, Purl. Out here that might be an insult, but in the grace that is the most precious thing. }
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \fi360\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 A solitary christian grave could be made out, with its double headstone, epitatphs sand-scoured to illegibility. }
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The way a lizard looks at you without really looking at you, head flat against the ground, eye swiveled all the way up in it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s socket to stare at the giant Mandrameen. , ever vigilant, ever alert. There was nothing around, but it didn\u8217\'92t know that. A lizard\u8217\'92s life must be exhausting, Mandri thought, having to be on-guard the whole day through, from moment to moment, because it just doesn\u8217\'92t have the presence of mind to be able see into the near future.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 A of poop-tails thousand strong. Mandri woundered aloud why they piss on their tails, and Obo said that when it gets too hot (and it always gets too hot), Piss-tail lizards cup their hind feet, and then evacuate their cloacal contents onto them, allowing them to rub their tails in it, and the do this so that when they raise their tails into the air, the water evaporates, and in so doing, draws the heat from the body. Seb overheard this, gargled urine to lubricate the throat. Because when the heat dries out the throat. Desert normalizes body functions, stops being gross, because the body is one the few things that exists.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Under my feet are some holes which have been burrowed by foxes and jackls. At night they descend stealthily from their haunts in their difficult search for food, and appear silhouetted against the sky. This evening they appear to sense my presence and stay in hiding, perhaps wondering at t his stranger who has come to disturb their peace. The mound is covered with white bones which represent the accumulated evidence of their hunts.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 A lizard is now sending forth his howl, half-cry and half-threat. All the dogs of the arab village immediately take up his challange, and for a moment the peace is upset by howling and barking. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 I should like to find a reason for all this desolation. Why should a flourishing city, the seat of an empire, have completely disappeared? Is it the fulfilment of a prophetic curse that changed a superb temple int oa den of jackals? probably we ourselves and our own achievents may becom an object of search for peoples to come?}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \fi360\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 It seemed to me that the chief characteristic of night in the desert was not darkness but this light that was not the sun\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s.}
\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 For the majority of the journey was spent with his head shrouded in a burnoose. Bleak and tedious sameness.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 They took up a southeast Charnel road called the Hafthir road. A lot of pilgrim skeletons on the Hafthir. One of these skeletons was walking, southeast as well, and Ayramun overtook this hobbling creature with. The man stared at them with winkless eyes, his was like skin like paper, and his ribs were countable through the window in his yellow haircloth habit, his emaciated stomach was sucked in to his vertebral column.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 This pilgrim thought Ayram was Solraheen enfleshed. Ayram paused, sponged water onto the old man\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s lips, and they made a brief, whispered exchange which Mandri could not hear. Moteah told the pilgrim that there was a well just a day to the west if he could make it. The pilgrim said thanks, but he\u8217\'92ll keep to the road.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri gave the pilgrim one of Seb\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s rocks.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Their passing put a joy in the pilgrim\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eyes. His eyes betraying that this was his final test, and dessicated, a tear of joy that he was done.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Uprooting huge bushels of twigs. Everyone looked like a porcupine.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri wondered ifhe were the only person to come backk from the dead, only ayram.}
\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 One evening, share moral stories}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93There was a witch who dwelt on a pillar where the sea meets the Saki desert. She gained much fame throughout the land for her talent of divination. If you caught a karkoot lizard, and brought her its stomach in a jar of brine, she would fortell your future. So great were her talents that people hunted karkoots until there were none left. Now, there\u8217\'92s a lot of stories about this witch. The one I find interesting is a story about a carpenter\u8217\'92s son, a profligate child\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 that means he was wasteful with his father\u8217\'92s money. Whether it was beer, women, or friends, he spent money without caution. His father wasn\u8217\'92t rich, he was, after all, a carpenter. This boy simply had no respect for the work his father put in to provide him with what he had. In a way, you can\u8217\'92t blame the child. Most of his life he was too young to understand how hard his father worked, and when he was old enough to know, the father\u8217\'92s efforts were out of sight because the father had paid for schooling in another city in the hopes his son would surpass him in society.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93So, the son, living in a different city, he takes the father\u8217\'92s money that was meant for his education, and instead, he spends it on beer, women, and friends. Ultimately, his life\u8217\'92s prospects come to nothing.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93When the father finds out that his own son has beggared them both, his rage\u8230\'85his rage is profound. It might be hard for you two to understand because you don\u8217\'92t have children-\u8220\'93}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Neither do you,\u8221\'94 said Mandri.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yes, but you see, we Mazid are supremely empathetic creatures\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 not that you aren\u8217\'92t, it\u8217\'92s simply different\u8230\'85let me try to paint the father\u8217\'92s rage for you\u8230\'85I think you two, considering your present circumstances, have some sympathy for the idea that human life is some kind of mistake. It lacks purpose. Contrast that with me, I was built for an explicit purpose, I }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 know}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  what my purpose is. You, however, you must have a nagging sense of the absence of yours. If you }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 do}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  have a purpose, at least we can say that it is not at all clear what that purpose is \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  the Solitants admit as much\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 and what good does that do you? Think of it like this, if you ever find yourself blessed with wealth and health beyond comprehension, what happens to you then? I can tell you what happens, I\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92ve seen it in pop up in Hrkan royalty. Without anything to distract you, well you think you }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 should}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  be happy now that you\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92re swimming freely in your natural purpose, but that\u8217\'92s not what happens, what happens is you become bored. Totally bored. A boredom so thorough and complete that people kill themselves. This isn\u8217\'92t despair, it\u8217\'92s boredom. And this is the truth; a human\u8217\'92s natural state is boredom and its unbearable. So what does that say about your intrinsic natures? It says you have no intrinsic purpose.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What does any of this have to do with the carpenter?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Mandri, this the backdrop to every human struggle. You see, human purpose is }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 crafted, }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 and that means it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s something you can }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 lose}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 . And I put it to you that losing your purpose is the greatest horror you can experience. Don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t smile, Mandri, you of all people should know this. You\u8217\'92re so scared to lose your purpose that you won\u8217\'92t even make one in the first place. You\u8217\'92re sitting firmly in that third of all people who got burnt when they were young and have let that little taste of horror clam them up for the rest of their life. This isn\u8217\'92t a value judgment, in fact I think you\u8217\'92re sane to clam up. Then there\u8217\'92s that other third of people, religious types who hide their purpose in the metaphysical realm, so by definition it can\u8217\'92t be lost and so they don\u8217\'92t have to worry about it. Most of the rest make their family their purpose. The carpenter was such a man. His son was his challenge to the void. And he lost. And it wasn\u8217\'92t taken from him, it was }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 squandered}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 . That\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s worse than if his son were killed, because if his son were killed he could have moved into grief. But no, the father challenged the void, and the void had answered back by corrupting his son, turning him into the living embodiment of his life\u8217\'92s wasted labor. At least, that\u8217\'92s how the father saw it. How could he see different? As Seb might say, the man was who he was. And what did he do? He made a snuffbox and sent it with a messenger to his son. Inside was a note from the father which said, \u8216\'91you are going to die\u8217\'92. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93This message freaked the son out. He was a wastrel, but a self-obsessed wastrel; he didn\u8217\'92t want to die. For a month he never slept in the same place twice. He couldn\u8217\'92t enjoy himself. He couldn\u8217\'92t go to taverns or whorehouses for the fear of his father lying in wait. So what did he do? He decided to go and see the witch about it. If she could predict the future, then she could help him avoid his father\u8217\'92s wrath. So he found a karkoot lizard, stuck it in a jar of brine, and set off to see the witch.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93When he finally set foot in the witches cave, he said to her, \u8216\'91My own father is trying to kill me. What should I do?\u8217\'92 Unfortunately for him, this was the wrong kind of question to ask. The old witch dealt with facts, with certainties about the future. She wanted to hear questions like, \u8216\'91What will happen on third full moon?\u8217\'92, or, \u8216\'91When will the rains come?\u8217\'92, that sort of thing. When someone came along asking for advice, like, \u8216\'91What should I do?\u8217\'92, she got angry. But hers was a silent, vindictive anger. She smoked up and did the whole song and dance for the wastrel son, and when she was done she said to him, \u8216\'91When you leave this place, the first thought that enters your head is what you }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 will}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  do\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Needlessly ambiguous, but that was the point. This witch was old and long in the trade, and she knew what kind of customer this wastrel was and how her response would weigh on him. And it did weigh on him. He jumped to the conclusion that his father was waiting just outside the cave, and that the first \u8216\'91thought\u8217\'92 that would enter his head would be a blade. So he didn\u8217\'92t leave. He stayed right there in that witches\u8217\'92 cave and refused to leave.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The witch of course, tried to shoo him out, but she couldn\u8217\'92t. Her plan had backfired. She was stuck with this idiot who was convinced that the moment he left her cave, he would be struck dead. The witch tried to tell him that his father couldn\u8217\'92t be sitting right outside the mouth of the cave for all eternity, but the son didn\u8217\'92t buy it. It\u8217\'92s not that he thought is father }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 was}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  always watching the cave, but that when he decided to leave, that\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s precisely when his father would show up.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The witch eventually gave up trying to convince the boy that he could walk outside safely, and she told him that he could stay if he did chores for her, like scrubbing the cave floor, cooking, and whatnot.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93After many, many years of this, the witch eventually died, and the carpenter\u8217\'92s son was no longer a carpenter\u8217\'92s son. Why? Because he had been the witch\u8217\'92s apprentice. He had learned how to divine the future by watching the witch read the folds in fish stomachs, and so he had become his own man with his own profession. The witch was dead, but people kept coming to the cave anyways. It is said that this former wastrel\u8217\'92s divinations transformed the lives of hundreds of thousands of people, for even kings would seek his sight to plan the courses of their wars.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The great irony of all this is that the note the carpenter sent to his son was not a threat. If you remember, the note said, \u8216\'91You are going to die\u8217\'92\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  that was a mere statement of fact; everybody dies. The father had no intention of hunting down his son. So there\u8217\'92s a sweetness in the knowledge that that simple message did more than any thing the father could have done to shape his son\u8217\'92s life. I don\u8217\'92t know if the father lived long enough to discover that his son had become a great diviner and shaped the course of history, but I like to think that the abatement of his despair would have been most sublime, for he had, unknowingly, triumphed against the void.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri said, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I wonder if the witch knew that the son would become a diviner.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Purl said, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Of course she did. She was a diviner. She divined the future and knew what to say to make it happen. The carpenter\u8217\'92s son was as much her son as the carpenters.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Then why did she try to convince him to leave?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s part of the telling, Mandri, don\u8217\'92t think too much about it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well, it\u8217\'92s a poor telling.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Obo\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eyes lit up. \u8220\'93You think you can do better?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I do.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Then }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I know a story about a son. A godly son. Upright in his parent\u8217\'92s eyes and in Solraheen\u8217\'92s. That is, until the day he met a girl.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Typical\u8221\'94, Purl groaned.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Shameful to relate, the story of a young man kidnapped by demons to a satin bed. The demons stroked his body in the most delicate of embraces, and fondled his uglies with their half-human, half-animal appendages, so as to win a depraved victory over him. Inspired by the grace of Solraheen, the young man bit off his tongue. The emphatic pain, and then the coldness of death, rescued him from his lust.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 They asked Purl if she had any stories to tell. She flashed a meek smile and said no. Mandri and Obo wouldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t have it. Mandri said that he would bet the weight of Purl\u8217\'92s pack that she knew at least one story. Obo said that stories are what human beings }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 do}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , so it was impossible that she shouldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t know any. But the issue wasn\u8217\'92t that Purl didn\u8217\'92t know any stories, it was that she didn\u8217\'92t like how excited she got when she told them.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You know what,\u8221\'94 said Purl, \u8220\'93I\u8217\'92ve got a story about a different kind of son. It\u8217\'92s a story about the son of a red-crowned lizard. And red-crown lizards, if you don\u8217\'92t know, like to live in mounds made out of their own shit.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That\u8217\'92s not quite true,\u8221\'94 said Obo.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It is in this story. This lizard family\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 a mother, father, and their forty children\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 they lived in a mound made entirely out of their own poop. Whenever someone had to poop, they looked for a wall that needed mending and they let loose. Then the sun sun baked the shit into a shit brick and that was that.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Charming,\u8221\'94 said Obo.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Now, one lizard son didn\u8217\'92t like living in a mound a shit. His parents asked him, \u8216\'91What\u8217\'92s wrong? Why don\u8217\'92t you like it here?\u8217\'92 and the son said, obviously, \u8216\'91because this place is a mound of shit.\u8217\'92 The father pretended to laugh, and said, \u8216\'91Very funny. Now go fix the front door\u8217\'92.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93This lizard son was dutiful son, and so he did what his father commanded, he lifted his tail and pooped on front door. Still\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 he didn\u8217\'92t like living in a mound of shit. He went back to the father and said, \u8216\'91Why can\u8217\'92t we be like the finches, who live in cups of sticks and moss? Why can\u8217\'92t we be like the rats, who live deep underground in burrows? Why can\u8217\'92t we be like the humans, who live wherever they want?\u8217\'92}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The father said, \u8216\'91We do not have wings, so where are going to get sticks and moss? We do not have digging claws, so how can we dig into the earth? We do not have beer, so how can we live wherever we want? No, my son, we have to count on what we do have, and what we do have is poop. Now go chew a hole in the living room wall, we\u8217\'92re looking to expand.\u8217\'92}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Dutifully, the son chewed a hole in the living room wall. His mouth was full of his family\u8217\'92s leavings, and he realized, now more than ever, that he didn\u8217\'92t like living in a mound of shit. He decided then and there that enough was enough and he was going to leave. So he wiggled out and set off into the desert.\u8217\'92}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93He didn\u8217\'92t return home for five years, which, for a red-crown lizard, made him old enough to be a grandfather. His parents were long dead. One of his lizard sisters now owned the mound.\u8217\'92}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The sister, trying to be a most gracious host, invited her long lost brother inside for dinner. The brother declined. When the sister asked why, the brother answered, \u8216\'91Because you live in a mound of shit. I\u8217\'92ve traveled the world and have slept in the houses of birds, and rats, and humans, and I\u8217\'92ve even snuck into a snake\u8217\'92s den! None of them were so foul as this.\u8217\'92}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The sister said, \u8216\'91Come now, brother, it\u8217\'92s not that bad. We\u8217\'92ve added a second floor.\u8217\'92 The brother said, \u8216\'91No thank, you,\u8217\'92 and he left. As he left, he heard his sister shout at one of her many children, saying, \u8216\'91The floor should be clean enough to eat off!\u8217\'92}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The old brother was sad at this parting. After all the glorious homes he\u8217\'92d seen, it hurt to see his sister and her family living in such squalor. He decided to do something about it. He thought that all they needed was a push out the door and they\u8217\'92d see for themselves that a mound of shit is the worst kind of house to live in.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93So he journeyed back to the snake whose home he\u8217\'92d snuck into. This time, however, he revealed himself to the snake. He said to the snake, \u8216\'91I know you want to eat me, but if you can hold your appetite, I will lead you to a mound of shit that is crawling with lizards. It will be the easiest feast of your life.\u8217\'92}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The snake was skeptical. It asked the old lizard, \u8216\'91Why would you betray your kin like this?\u8217\'92 And the lizard said, \u8216\'91I will you lead you there on the condition that you promise to leave at least one boy and one girl alive, so that they can carry on the family name. Also, and this is the most important thing, you have to completely destroy that mound of shit.\u8217\'92}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The snake wasn\u8217\'92t sure if he wanted to do it. He had no arms and legs, so if he wanted to destroy the mound he\u8217\'92d have to roll around in it. But the promise of an easy meal was too good to pass up, so he said to the old lizard, \u8216\'91lead on\u8217\'92.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The lizard led the snake back to his sister\u8217\'92s home, and the snake did what he promised. He ate the sister and her husband, and most of their children too, and he rolled around in the pile of dried shit, crushing it into dust.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Only two lizards survived. A boy and a girl. Without a home they were forced to wander around in the desert. Their old, kinslaying uncle followed them from afar, eager to see how they fared, but not wanting to intrude on their new lives and the experiences that awaited them. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Eventually, the young brother and sister got tired of not having a permanent home. The girl said to her brother, \u8216\'91I just want my own bed to sleep in.\u8217\'92}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The boy said, \u8216\'91I wish the same. We should build a house.\u8217\'92}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93\u8216\'91How do you build a house?\u8217\'92}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93\u8216\'91I don\u8217\'92t know. What was it grandfather was always saying?\u8217\'92}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93\u8216\'91He always said that all we\u8217\'92ve got is our poop.\u8217\'92 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93And it just so happened that right next to them was a brick of poop that one of them had left sitting there from the day before. And I\u8217\'92m sure you know what happened next\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 the two lizards built a new mound of poop to live in.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Now, when the old lizard saw that his niece and nephew had reverted back to the old ways, he became distressed. He wandered back into the snake\u8217\'92s den, and the snake, surprised to see him, asked him, \u8216\'91Why have you returned?\u8217\'92 To this the old lizard replied, \u8216\'91Because they can\u8217\'92t think of anything else but shit.\u8217\'92 Then the snake ate the old lizard, and that\u8217\'92s the end of the story.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri screwed up his nose and said, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That\u8217\'92s not how that story goes.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Purl sneered back. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That\u8217\'92s how it goes, because that\u8217\'92s how I said it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri tried to appeal to Obo for an unbiased judgment, but Obo said, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Purl\u8217\'92s right. The storyteller makes the rules.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Fine,\u8221\'94 said Mandri. \u8220\'93But it\u8217\'92s a little contrived for my tastes.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What does that mean?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well, It\u8217\'92s about Hrk, isn\u8217\'92t it? Hrk is the mound of poop. Civilization is the mound of poop? Everyone is just too inured to that way to imagine a better way of doing things?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You said it, not me.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Oh come on, that\u8217\'92s exactly what it means.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92re the artist. You would know wouldn\u8217\'92t you?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Your damned right. And let me give you some advice: good art leaves room for ambiguity. That\u8217\'92s why you can\u8217\'92t tell a story so contrived, it\u8217\'92s too\u8230\'85it\u8217\'92s too obvious, and if something is obvious, no one takes it seriously.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I thought you said there\u8217\'92s no such thing as good art?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I did. But that\u8217\'92s another matter altogether.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Whatever.\u8221\'94}
