\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 After a week they came into to the Tib desert, or the Black desert, for it was a black plain with a hard floor of small stones tarred in rock-varnish. These stones were inset into the earth, and tightly interlocked like a Hrkan road.  }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 In the hours of the afternoon sun, the rocks underfoot were hot enough to blister bare skin in seconds. The stones were smooth, but such was the heat that traveling here would wear holes in the shoes. And this seemed to slow their progress.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 They walked the Tib, south and east, and day after day they moved forward and nothing changed. Always the same,  }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Nights in the Tib were spent huddled around three twiggy fires. It wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t the heat that provided comfort, though the nights were cold, it was the smell, for suspended above these miniature fires were a tin bowls filled with scented wax, smelling of carrion, and in the mornings, the hardened wax would be thick with the fuzzy brown bodies of cusiloe flys who were looking for meat in which to implant their eggs.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The flies live in the earth, squeezed deep into the crevices of the interlocking rocks, and the odors of flesh, living or otherwise, draws them from hibernation - but only at night. Like reasonable creatures, they don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t come out to bake in the sun.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 As soon as the red lip of the sun peeks up in the east, everyone rises and checks themselves to make sure they hadn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t been impregnated. If a fly did get under the skin, and the eggs were allowed to hatch, removing them would be a painful ordeal, potentially fatal. Seb described the larvae - pulsing white thumbs with two fangs the length of fingernails. Pull them out and they can rip the flesh and leave a hole that will get infected. You look for them by feeling. Skin is too dark to see the soft little welts, especially Moto and Moteah's skin, so you\u8217\'92ve got to feel around for a hardened, coin-sized bump, like a callous on the palm, but maybe it\u8217\'92s on your thigh, on your prick, in your armpit, upon your back, and since you can\u8217\'92t reach your back you\u8217\'92ve got to have someone else do it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Moteah and Moto checked each other. Ayram and Elrahet checked each other. Mandri smiled at Purl but this was not reciprocated. He was paired with Seb, and neither were happy about the arrangement, Mandri because Seb\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s fingers were oily, and Seb because he thought Mandri might miss a . }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Moteah checked Purl\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s back.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Nobody checked Obo. He said the flies wouldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t bother him.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 They\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d scrape the paste of dead flies from the surface of the wax, save them for food, and then they\u8217\'92d be on their way again, a short sprint in the half-light hours betwixt the sun and the moon. When the sun rose again, they\u8217\'92d stop, pitch little shelters, and rest until worst of the heat had passed.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It was a lurching way to travel, and it felt to Mandri that they made no progress. Day after day and scenery did not change at all. To the north, a flat plain of pebbles for as far as the eye could see. To the south, a flat plain for as far as the eye could see. To the east and to the west it was the same - flat for as far as the eye could see. They\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d walk at a hurried pace for hours, they\u8217\'92d stop, and Mandri could swear he saw the same damn pattern of rocks that he\u8217\'92d seen four times before.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Moving like this, out of rhythm and in unfamiliar hours, skating on the surface of an endless black stone sea, it changed the perception of time. There were no new spikes of memory around which an hour could congeal. No new sights, no new sounds, and no new conversations because the heat of the day and the cold of night tempered everyone into the same person; short responses, shrugging shoulders, faces set in the same tight-lipped frown that said, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I just want to get through it\u8221\'94. And that\u8217\'92s who everyone was, bundled, muddled balls of just-get-through-it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Except for Obo, of course. Obo remained genial and solicitous.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s fretful eye glancing north, looking for Hrks.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 There was nowhere to hide in this desert. If they ever came, he would see them, and they would definitely see him, walking pillar that he was. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 No one could see the Hrks, but they could see Ayram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s worry. Their pace quickened, and they stayed moving until anyone spotted the first cusiloe fly crack out of the ground.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 A ray of joy strafed Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s heart when he saw the brown peaks of the Goree mountains. They came up all at once, a long, dark lumpy line waiting there on the horizon. Still no sign of the Hrks.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 They pushed through the sun, and evening brought them to the mountain\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s feet, for the Goree had no hills, it was flat land all the way up to their bases, with a dust of red-iron dirt filled in the recesses between the pebbles, and then covered them up completely by the time that reached red rock.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The mountains themselves were buttresses against the desert wind, and as such their mottled red faces looked they\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d just been attacked by claws the size of a river. Deep, scoring cuts, sweep, like great, static Ergs.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram led them south, and now that they were safe from flies, he led them long into the night. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri whispered to Purl, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What if the pass is north of here? How does he know which way to go? \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93He remembers it,\u8221\'94 said Purl, as if that were a perfectly reasonable thing to say.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 But there was just no way that Ayram could have dead-reckoned it all the from Minting Rock. The featureless Tib would have made that impossible, and the arc of the sun was more of a guideline than a precise measure.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He should ask the man himself, but Mandri decided not to, and good thing too, because the next person who spoke drew Ayram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s ire.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It was Seb.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He had to poop.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram shushed him, but Seb insisted.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92re the one that made me eat those flies!\u8221\'94 Seb said.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Alright!\u8221\'94 Ayram exclaimed, and he stopped the train. \u8220\'93Just be quick and quiet.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It ain\u8217\'92t gonna be quiet, I can tell ya that. Matter of fact, ain\u8217\'92t gonna be quick, either.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Seb sauntered off into the rocks, and disappeared amongst the shadows.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri dumped Obo onto the ground, then went to Moto and asked for some twigs to make a fire to calm the night chill.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No fires,\u8221\'94 Ayram said.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We\u8217\'92ve got to be quiet, and we\u8217\'92ve got to pass unseen.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Won\u8217\'92t the Mazydariga know where we are regardless?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Moto answered, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s not that Hrks we\u8217\'92re worried about. See, there\u8217\'92s two kinds tribes in the Goree: those who want to kill you, and those who want to steal your stuff. Either way, you end up dead.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well, if they\u8217\'92re up in the mountains, won\u8217\'92t they have seen us coming from miles away?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Probably not, actually. There\u8217\'92s not much reason for them to be watching the Tib, because it\u8217\'92s not a journey often made. We might have slipped through and if we have, don\u8217\'92t want to spoil it with a fire.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Tomorrow morning.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The light of day?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yes.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93\u8220\'93But\u8230\'85 you just said that everyone wants to kill us.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The Goree pass is neutral ground, so long as you pass in the day.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93And who makes sure of that?\u8221\'94 Obo asked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Custom.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Hah!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Obo\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s laugh drew a snarl from Moto. \u8220\'93Custom may mean nothing to you,\u8221\'94 he said, \u8220\'93but desert customs have a bounded logic which demands respect. They have preserved us for thousands of years. Every tribesman knows that if they violate the Goree Pass, then .\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Obo said, with ebullient eyes, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I didn\u8217\'92t laugh because I doubted you. I laughed because I believed you.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well, I don\u8217\'92t believe him,\u8221\'94 Mandri said.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93But you should,\u8221\'94 said Obo.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92ve met enough people to know that custom doesn\u8217\'92t stop people from looking out themselves when it comes down to it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Have you ever heard of the Old Believers?\u8221\'94 Obo asked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The who?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93There was once a tribe called the Old Believers. They lived in an alluvial plain just south of . They had strange ways of worshiping Solraheen, so to incorporate them into world of Hrk we had to reform their religion. The plan was to do it piecemeal, over generations, so as not to cause a stir. Don\u8217\'92t start with the relgion itself, start with some of the customs to soften them up. The first thing we did is we told them to not write Solraheen with two L\u8217\'92s. And we told them to use an open thumb when they make the sign of the brothers.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93So?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Guess what they did.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93They didn\u8217\'92t want to do it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93They built warehouses out of resin-rich timber, locked themselves inside, and then burnt it all down. An entire tribe of ten-thousand people dead in one night. They killed themselves and their children over a single L and an open thumb.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t believe you.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Oh, it happened\u8230\'85 It happened. If you ever make it to Jeket\u8217\'92s library, you should look for a book on the histories of the Old Believers.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yeah, I\u8217\'92m not going to do that.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I had never met a religious folk who\u8217\'92d been so truly possessed by belief. I\u8217\'92ve seen tribes tickled by it, sure, but not so possessed as to kill their own babes, kneeling in prayer as they did. The priests in Jeket only ever kneel to peek under a woman\u8217\'92s robe.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Elrahet was sitting. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92re the Mazyd that killed the Old Believers?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Are you not listening? They killed themselves.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Elrahet grunted a , and Ayram said that was enough.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 They sheltered for the night behind a jumble of boulders which sheltered them from the icy western wind. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram shared some stern words with Seb when he got back from his fecal excursion.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 All save Ayram lay down to rest. }
